<div class="recipe-container">
    <h1>Paneer 65 Recipe</h1>

    <div class="recipe-description">
        <p><strong>Paneer 65</strong> is a spicy and crispy South Indian appetizer made with paneer (Indian cottage cheese), coated in a flavorful batter, deep-fried, and tossed in a spicy tempering. This dish is perfect as a snack or starter for parties and special occasions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ingredients">
        <h2>Ingredients</h2>
        <div class="ingredient-list">
            <div class="ingredient-item">
                <p><strong>For the Batter:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>200g Paneer (cubed)</li>
                    <li>2 tbsp Cornflour</li>
                    <li>2 tbsp All-purpose flour</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Rice flour (for extra crispiness)</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Ginger-garlic paste</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Red chili powder</li>
                    <li>1/2 tsp Turmeric powder</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Garam masala</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Cumin powder</li>
                    <li>1/2 tsp Black pepper powder</li>
                    <li>Salt to taste</li>
                    <li>Water (as required to make a thick batter)</li>
                    <li>Oil (for deep frying)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="ingredient-item">
                <p><strong>For the Tempering:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>1 tbsp Oil</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Mustard seeds</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Cumin seeds</li>
                    <li>2-3 Green chilies (slit)</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Garlic (chopped)</li>
                    <li>1 sprig Curry leaves</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Yogurt</li>
                    <li>1/2 tsp Red chili powder</li>
                    <li>1/4 tsp Turmeric powder</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Tomato ketchup</li>
                    <li>Fresh coriander leaves (for garnish)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cooking-instructions">
        <h2>How to Cook</h2>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Prepare the Batter:</strong> In a bowl, mix cornflour, all-purpose flour, rice flour, ginger-garlic paste, red chili powder, turmeric, garam masala, cumin powder, black pepper, and salt. Add water gradually to make a thick batter.</li>
            <li><strong>Coat the Paneer:</strong> Add the paneer cubes to the batter and coat them well.</li>
            <li><strong>Deep Fry the Paneer:</strong> Heat oil in a pan and deep-fry the paneer cubes until golden brown and crispy. Remove and place them on a paper towel to absorb excess oil.</li>
            <li><strong>Prepare the Tempering:</strong> In another pan, heat 1 tbsp oil, add mustard seeds, cumin seeds, green chilies, and curry leaves. Sauté for a few seconds.</li>
            <li>Add chopped garlic and sauté until fragrant. Then, add yogurt, red chili powder, turmeric, and tomato ketchup. Mix well.</li>
            <li>Add the fried paneer to the tempering and toss well to coat.</li>
            <li><strong>Garnish & Serve:</strong> Garnish with fresh coriander leaves and serve hot.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="tips">
        <h2>Tips & Variations</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>For extra crispiness, double-fry the paneer.</li>
            <li>Adjust the spice level by adding more or fewer chilies.</li>
            <li>To make it healthier, you can air-fry or bake the paneer instead of deep-frying.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="serve">
        <h2>Serving Suggestions</h2>
        <p>Serve Paneer 65 hot with mint chutney, tamarind sauce, or tomato ketchup. It pairs well with naan, roti, or as a side dish with biryani.</p>
    </div>
</div>
